\n<Manu><WordWrap>Hello, are you Madam Oggay?
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Why, hello there! I am Madam Oggay and might I ask who are you and are you a contestant in the contest?
\n<Manu><WordWrap>My name is Manu and yes I am a contestant of the contest. I am here to-
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Oh good!, Finally someone came already. I was dying of boredom just for other contestants to come. What happened to the other contestants anyway?
\n<Manu><WordWrap>Well you seee Esbeche hid from everyone from the contest and -
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>TSK ESBECHE! Such a nuisance when it comes to that. Always complaining about the contest and cannot take his mind out of it.
\n<Manu><WordWrap>Ok? And while he was hiding from everyone people got trapped in caves in sear-
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>OH MY WHAT A HORRIBLE THING! Did those people made it out? What happened to them?
\n<Manu><WordWrap>COULD I JUST GET TO THE POINT ALREADY!
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>You may...
\n<Manu><WordWrap>I came here to compete in the last challenge of the contest. I have cleared both of the areas required to continue.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>I see...But may I ask what is the real reason as to why you wanted to compete in this contest?
\n<Manu><WordWrap>The reason why I competed is to have my culinary dreams come true.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Is there more reason as to why you wanted to come to this competition besides your culinary dreams?
\n<Manu><WordWrap>...
\n<Manu><WordWrap>Another reason is that I wanted to learn the value of cooking. I have lost my self in the pursuit of culinary that I have lost my culture in some sense.
\n<Manu><WordWrap>I came here to learn and re evaluate my cooking prowess. That is the other reason as to why I came to this contest...
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>I see...Well I'll let you compete in this last challenge of this contest.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>This challenge will be simple. I want you to get two recipies from the caves on both sides of my house.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>The recipies are the Bibingka recipe and Cassava Cake to make a base for the Kakanin platter.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>If you can bring back the recipes of Bibingka and Cassava Cake, come back to me so that we can create the Kakanin.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>The recipes are located at caves between my houses. Once you enter the caves you have to navigate around and find the recipe's for the Bibingka and Cassava Cake.
\n<Manu><WordWrap>Understood!
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Now hurry along, we don't have the whole day now.

\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Here it is Manu...
You have obtained ingredients for Bibingka and Cassava Cake!!!

\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Have you made the Bibingka?
\n<Manu><WordWrap>Yes Madam Oggay I have made the Bibingka. Here it its.
You gave away 1x Bibingka...
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Ah, perfect! Bibingka is a unique type of dish that is loved by many people here.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>People alway's misinterpret Bibingka as a dish only for the poor people and as a street food. But that's not the case.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Bibingka is a dish that that symbolizes togetherness because of its sticky nature that we cannot be easily be seperated or defined by social status and by who we are.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>No matter who you are or where you came from, Bibingka brings people together and is enjoyed when there is plenty of people to be with.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Now have you made the Cassava Cake?
\n<Manu><WordWrap>Yes Madam Oggay I have made the Cassava Cake. Here it its.
You gave away 1x Cassava Cake...
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Very nice that you have made the Cassava Cake.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Cassava wasn't the most popular dish to be liked by people due to its high difficulty in creating the dish.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Reason as to why Cassava was popular, is because it was a poor man's "meal" that was easy to cultivate in the harsh environments during harsh times.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>After a while, the people were adapting with the food and making various dishes that made the Cassava Cake a staple dish here in Gastropolis.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>All though people only make Cassava cake during special occassions or festivals.
\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>Since everything seems in all prepared, lets head to the kitchen on the right to prepare the Kakanin for the people.

\n<Madam Oggay><WordWrap>I have already prepared the other dishes needed for the Kakanin. All we have to do is to cut the Bibingka and Cassava Cake, and place them in a properly order along with the dishes for the Kakanin
